"""
MKT Context Commentary — Joshua chapters 21–23
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-joshua-21-23.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/joshua.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/joshua.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch21: Levitical city dispersal explained against Num 35 and Gen 49:7 background
- Ch21: Hebron city-vs-fields distinction (v12) resolves the Caleb/Aaron tension
- Ch21: vv43-45 are the Deuteronomistic theological summary — treated as climactic
- Ch22: The altar crisis read against Deut 12 centralization law and Baal-Peor precedent
- Ch22: Phinehas's role deliberately echoes his Num 25 action
- Ch23: Farewell speech patterned after Moses's Deuteronomy addresses — conditional blessings/curses
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOSHUA = {
  "21": {
    "1": '<p>The Levitical appeal comes from "the heads of the Levitical families" — the clan leadership, not just priests. They present their case to the two civil authorities (Eleazar the priest, Joshua) and the tribal heads: a tripartite leadership structure that mirrors the political organization of the Sinai covenant community. The appeal is framed as a legal claim based on a divine command, not a request for charity.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The command cited is Num 35:1-8: "Command the Israelites to give the Levites towns to live in from the inheritance the Israelites will possess." The Levites had no tribal territory — YHWH himself was their inheritance (Deut 18:1-2; Num 18:20). The towns were not land grants in the sense of agricultural inheritance but designated residential areas with attached pasturelands for livestock.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Obeying the LORD\'s command" marks this distribution as the legal fulfillment of Num 35, just as the tribal allotments fulfilled the patriarchal promises. The Levitical town allocation is the final element of the distribution — the entire land-grant program (tribes + Levites) is now complete, structured by the single overarching divine command given through Moses.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The Kohathite priority within the Levitical allocation mirrors the camp arrangement in Num 3-4: the Kohathites camped immediately around the tabernacle and bore the ark and holy objects. Their cities in Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin place Aaron\'s descendants near Jerusalem — the future site of the permanent sanctuary. The priestly assignment to the southern tribal heartland is geographically providential for the later Davidic-Solomonic temple establishment.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The non-Aaronic Kohathites receive ten cities from the central tribes (Ephraim, Dan, half-Manasseh). The Kohathites were responsible for carrying the tabernacle furniture (Num 4:1-20); placing them centrally, near Shechem and the Ephraim highlands, positioned them close to the early sanctuary at Shiloh.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Gershonites receive cities from the northern tribes (Issachar, Asher, Naphtali, half-Manasseh in Bashan). In the wilderness, the Gershonites carried the tabernacle curtains and coverings (Num 4:21-28). Their northern dispersion extends Levitical presence throughout Galilee and the Transjordanian north, areas that would be most vulnerable to Canaanite and later Aramean religious influence.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The Merarites, who carried the tabernacle frames and hardware (Num 4:29-33), receive twelve cities from the Transjordanian and Zebulun tribes. Their dispersion through Reuben, Gad, and Zebulun ensures Levitical presence in the territories most geographically isolated from the central sanctuary — the regions most at risk of religious drift.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The repeated compliance formula — "just as the LORD had commanded through Moses" — closes the lot-casting procedure as it opened the land distribution in ch13. Every stage of the land program (Caleb\'s request, Judah\'s allotment, Joseph\'s complaint, Zelophehad\'s daughters, Levitical cities) is explicitly grounded in Mosaic command. The narrator insists that the distribution was not Israel\'s negotiated arrangement but the execution of a pre-specified divine plan.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The detailed city lists that follow (vv9-42) have the character of administrative records. The specificity — naming individual towns with their pastureland grants — suggests archival sources. Similar land administration documents survive from ANE contexts (Ugaritic administrative tablets, Nuzi real-estate records). The list also served a practical function: it established which towns were Levitical property, preventing future alienation.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Aaron\'s descendants receive priority within the Kohathite lot — a reflection of the Aaronic priesthood\'s status. The Aaronic line had been specifically designated for priestly service at the altar and in the holy of holies (Exod 28-29; Num 18:1-7). Their cities cluster around the future capital area, positioning them for the temple cult that would eventually replace the portable tabernacle.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Kiriath-arba = Hebron. The parenthetical "Arba was the forefather of Anak" recalls the giants who made the spies despair in Num 13:33 and identifies Hebron as the Anakim\'s ancestral city. The city is now assigned to Aaron\'s priestly descendants — the strongest possible rebuke to the fear that Hebron\'s Anakim had inspired. What the Exodus generation was too afraid to claim becomes priestly property.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The fields and villages are Caleb\'s personal possession (ch14:6-15, 15:13-19), while the city itself is priestly property. This dual ownership distinguishes the urban settlement (Levitical) from the agricultural land (tribal). The arrangement reflects ANE property law in which land and urban property could be held under different ownership structures. It resolves the apparent tension between Caleb\'s Hebron grant and the priestly Hebron allocation.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Hebron\'s status as a city of refuge — established in ch20:7 — makes it doubly significant: priestly city and asylum city. The conjunction of these functions places the management of capital cases (asylum) under priestly supervision, consistent with the judicial role of priests in Deut 17:8-13 (difficult cases referred to the priests and judges at the central place).</p>',
    "14": '<p>Jattir, Eshtemoa — these Judean towns in the southern highlands will reappear in the David narrative. When David was a fugitive in the wilderness of Paran, he distributed plunder from Ziklag to "the elders of Judah" in Bethel, Ramoth-negev, Jattir, and other towns (1 Sam 30:27-31). The Levitical towns appear in the background of the Davidic story as recognized communities with established priestly and Levitical inhabitants.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Holon, Debir — Debir (Kiriath-Sepher) is the scribal center whose capture by Othniel was the first act of the judges (Josh 15:15-17). Its assignment to the Aaronic line connects it to the priestly scribal tradition. The names carry a cumulative weight in the narrative: places associated with conquest, clan traditions, and the emerging story of the settlement all appear in this list.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Beth-shemesh ("House of the Sun") was a town on the border of Judah and Dan, later famous as the place where the ark returned from Philistine captivity and the Levites received it (1 Sam 6:12-15). Its assignment here as a Levitical town explains why Levites were available to receive the ark when it arrived — a detail that becomes narratively significant three centuries later.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Gibeon and Geba are assigned to Benjamin and given to the Levites. Gibeon (Josh 9) was the Hivite city whose treaty with Israel had just been described; its assignment as a Levitical city integrates the Gibeonites further into the Israelite religious infrastructure. Gibeon later becomes a significant cultic site — the great high place where the tabernacle stood and Solomon offered sacrifices (1 Kgs 3:4; 2 Chr 1:3-6).</p>',
    "18": '<p>Anathoth — this Benjaminite Levitical city will become famous as the hometown of Jeremiah (Jer 1:1). Abiathar, one of David\'s priests, is eventually exiled there by Solomon (1 Kgs 2:26). The priestly connection to Anathoth, established here in the land distribution, explains its association with prophetic and priestly families in later texts.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The Aaronic priestly total: thirteen cities from the tribes of Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin. The geographic concentration of Aaron\'s descendants in the southern heartland — the territory that would become the kingdom of Judah — has lasting implications for the Davidic dynasty\'s priestly support and the Jerusalem temple\'s staffing.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The non-Aaronic Kohathites receive their allotment from Ephraim — the dominant central tribe. Shechem, the first city listed (v21), had been a covenant-assembly site since Abram (Gen 12:6) and would be where the twelve tribes reaffirmed the covenant under Joshua (Josh 24). Placing a Levitical city at Shechem maintained cultic presence at one of Israel\'s most sacred sites.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Shechem as a city of refuge appears here (also 20:7). Its dual role — asylum city and Levitical residence — again connects judicial and cultic functions. Gezer, assigned here but not yet captured (10:33), would remain unconquered until Pharaoh gave it as a dowry when Solomon married his daughter (1 Kgs 9:16-17). The assignment anticipates a future possession.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Kibzaim and Beth-horon complete the Ephraim Kohathite allotment. Beth-horon (upper and lower) controlled the critical pass descending from the central highlands to the coastal plain — strategically among the most important routes in Canaan. The hailstone battle of ch10 was fought precisely here. Its Levitical assignment placed Levites at a key geographic and military chokepoint.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The cities assigned to the Kohathite Levites from Dan — Eltekeh, Gibbethon — are towns in the western Shephelah and coastal plain, the territory Dan was assigned but never fully held. The Levitical assignment to Danite cities that the tribe itself struggled to hold reflects the tension in the settlement: the distribution was normative and ideal even where occupation lagged.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Aijalon — the Valley of Aijalon where the sun and moon stood still (10:12) — is assigned as a Levitical city. Gath-rimmon appears both here (Dan) and in v25 (Manasseh), which many textual critics consider a scribal duplication. Some manuscripts read "Bileam" for the Manassite city (cf. 1 Chr 6:70). The distribution\'s attention to exact cities rather than broad territories implies careful maintenance of these records.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The Kohathite cities from the half-tribe of Manasseh complete this clan\'s allotment. Taanach and Gath-rimmon are in the Jezreel Valley — the great plain of northern Israel that would be the site of major battles throughout the period of the judges and monarchy. Levitical presence in the Jezreel placed them in territory constantly contested between Israel and the surrounding nations.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The non-Aaronic Kohathite total: ten cities. The running totals (13 Aaronic, 10 non-Aaronic Kohathite, 13 Gershonite, 12 Merarite = 48 total) are editorially maintained throughout this chapter, giving it the character of an official census document rather than narrative history.</p>',
    "27": '<p>Golan in Bashan — assigned to the Gershonites from the half-tribe of Manasseh east of Jordan — was one of the six cities of refuge (20:8). Bashan\'s giant-king Og had been defeated in Num 21; the region is now organized into Israelite tribal and Levitical administration. Beeshterah (probably = Ashtaroth, Og\'s royal city) being given to Levites is significant: the Canaanite cultic center becomes Levitical property.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The Gershonite cities from Issachar — Kishon, Daberath, Jarmuth, En-gannim — are in the Jezreel Valley and the hills overlooking it. Daberath (= Daberath/Dabrath near Tabor) appears in the Deborah narrative (Judg 4:14, 5:15). The Levitical cities are scattered along the routes that would later be used by judges, prophets, and kings — not coincidentally positioned, the narrative suggests, but by YHWH\'s design.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The four Issachar cities complete the Gershonite northern allocation. The recurring "four cities" pattern (Issachar: 4, Asher: 4, Naphtali: 3, for a total of 13 Gershonite) follows the same accountant\'s precision seen throughout the chapter. The land distribution was administered with the bureaucratic care of a formal estate conveyance.</p>',
    "30": '<p>Mishal and Abdon from Asher — the coastal tribe in the western Galilee. Asher\'s territory included the Phoenician coast but the tribe never fully dislodged the Sidonians and Phoenician city-states (Judg 1:31-32). Levitical presence in these cities maintained Israelite religious identity in an area of persistent Canaanite-Phoenician cultural pressure.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Helkath and Rehob complete the Asher Gershonite allocation. Rehob appears in the Amarna letters as a significant Canaanite city. Its inclusion in the Levitical distribution represents the normative claim on territory that may have been only loosely held in practice.</p>',
    "32": '<p>Kedesh in Galilee — a city of refuge (20:7) — given to the Gershonites from Naphtali. Kedesh would become famous as the home of Barak (Judg 4:6) and the site of Deborah\'s summons. Its role as a refuge city explains the legal significance of the Sisera narrative: the woman Jael at Kedesh kills the Canaanite general who had fled to her tent — not to a city of refuge but to a private dwelling, a legally distinct situation.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The Gershonite total: thirteen cities across the northern territories. The geographic scope of the Gershonite distribution — from Manasseh in Bashan through Issachar, Asher, and Naphtali — covers the entire northern tier of the land, ensuring Levitical presence in the areas most distant from the central sanctuary and most exposed to Aramean, Phoenician, and later Assyrian influence.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The Merarite cities begin with Zebulun — Jokneam, Kartah, Dimnah, Nahalal. Jokneam is significant as a fortress controlling the western approach to the Jezreel Valley through the Carmel pass. Its Levitical designation placed Levites at a major military and commercial chokepoint. Nahalal appears in Judg 1:30 as a Canaanite city from which Zebulun "did not drive out the inhabitants" — another instance where the normative distribution preceded actual occupation.</p>',
    "35": '<p>Four Merarite cities from Zebulun. The brief format — name + pasturelands, name + pasturelands — is typical of administrative property records, stripped of narrative elaboration to emphasize the legal precision of the allocation.</p>',
    "36": '<p>Bezer from Reuben was one of the cities of refuge (20:8), located in the Transjordanian tableland. Jahaz is mentioned in Num 21:23 as the site of Sihon\'s defeat. These Transjordanian Merarite cities connect the Levitical distribution to the conquest narrative that preceded the land allotment — the very places where YHWH\'s power was first demonstrated in the land become Levitical settlements.</p>',
    "37": '<p>Kedemoth and Mephaath complete the Reubenite Merarite allotment. Kedemoth is noteworthy as the place from which Moses sent messengers to Sihon (Deut 2:26) — the diplomatic contact before the military victory. The town\'s assignment to the Levites links the Levitical distribution back to the pre-conquest negotiation narrative.</p>',
    "38": '<p>Ramoth in Gilead — another city of refuge (20:8) — given to the Gad Merarites. Ramoth-gilead will become one of the most fought-over cities in the later monarchy: the border fortress between Israel and Aram where Ahab died (1 Kgs 22) and where Jehu was anointed king (2 Kgs 9:1-13). Its Levitical designation did not prevent it from becoming a perpetual military objective.</p>',
    "39": '<p>Heshbon — Sihon\'s capital (Num 21:25) — is given to the Gad Merarites. Jazer, also in Gilead, was coveted by Reuben and Gad in Num 32:1 as suitable for livestock. The assignment of these Transjordanian towns — former Amorite strongholds — to Levitical residence completes the theological reversal: the cities of the defeated enemies become the dwelling places of YHWH\'s servants.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The Merarite total: twelve cities from Zebulun, Reuben, and Gad. The completion of the Merarite list closes the four-part Levitical distribution (Aaronic + non-Aaronic Kohathite + Gershonite + Merarite).</p>',
    "41": '<p>Forty-eight Levitical cities total, distributed throughout all twelve tribal territories (including the Transjordanian tribes). The number 48 is not arbitrary: Num 35:6-7 specified six cities of refuge among a larger number, and the total is programmatically complete. The dispersal of Levites throughout Israel — one of the tribes without a territorial block — fulfills Gen 49:7\'s word that Levi would be "scattered in Israel" (the curse on Simeon and Levi for the Shechem massacre). What Genesis framed as punishment, Deuteronomy and Joshua reframe as a providential mechanism for YHWH\'s instruction to be distributed throughout the entire land.</p>',
    "42": '<p>Each city\'s surrounding pastureland (<em>migrāš</em>) was legally specified in Num 35:4-5: a zone of 1,000 cubits from the city wall on all sides, then an additional 1,000-cubit zone for fields and vineyards. This standardized measurement ensured that Levites in every city had equivalent access to livestock grazing regardless of the surrounding tribal territory\'s wealth.</p>',
    "43": '<p>The first of three summary declarations: "the LORD gave Israel all the land he had sworn to give their ancestors." The land promise to Abraham (Gen 12:7, 15:18-21), Isaac (Gen 26:3), and Jacob (Gen 28:13) has been fulfilled. The formulation "<em>nātan</em> all the land" is total and unconditional — the narrator does not hedge with "most of the land" or "the land they were able to take." The theological claim is one of complete divine faithfulness, even if practical occupation remained partial.</p>',
    "44": '<p>The second declaration: "the LORD gave them rest on every side." The <em>nûaḥ</em> rest echoes the Deuteronomic promise of a place of rest where YHWH would set his name (Deut 12:9-10). "Not one of all their enemies had withstood them" is an absolute formulation — hyperbolic in the sense of the dominant outcome, not a denial of the ongoing resistance that Judges will document. The theological claim is that YHWH\'s intention to give the land was unobstructed.</p>',
    "45": '<p>The climactic third declaration: "Not a single word of all the good things the LORD had promised to the house of Israel went unfulfilled. Everything came true." This is the Deuteronomistic theology of promise-fulfillment stated in its most absolute form. The statement will be echoed and inverted in 23:14-15: just as every good promise has come true, so every threatened punishment will come true if the covenant is broken. The symmetry of divine word-keeping is the theological foundation of both the blessing and the warning.</p>'
  },
  "22": {
    "1": '<p>The formal dismissal of the eastern tribes (Reuben, Gad, half-Manasseh) fulfills the condition of Num 32:20-22: they had been permitted to settle east of Jordan on condition of fighting with their brothers until the land was at rest. The same three tribes that had raised a constitutional crisis in Num 32 (Moses feared a re-enactment of the spy disaster) are now honored for their covenant faithfulness.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Joshua\'s opening commendation — "you have done everything Moses the servant of the LORD commanded you" — is the highest possible praise in the Deuteronomistic framework. The compliance formula that has been the narrator\'s refrain throughout (1:7, 8:35, 11:15) is now applied to these tribes personally. They had kept both the Mosaic command and Joshua\'s commands — a two-level covenant loyalty.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"These many days right up to today" — the long duration of the campaign (cf. 11:18) is acknowledged. The eastern tribes had spent years away from their families and newly established territories east of Jordan. The sacrifice this represented in ANE terms — extended military service, absence from agricultural duties, risk of death in a foreign campaign — was substantial. Joshua\'s recognition names what they gave up.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The conditional discharge is complete: "the LORD your God has granted your fellow Israelites the rest he promised." The fulfilment of the rest (21:44) is the trigger for the eastern tribes\' release. Joshua frames the dismissal in covenant terms: the rest is YHWH\'s gift to the western tribes, not simply a strategic assessment that the campaign is over. The eastern tribes may return because YHWH has acted, not merely because the war is won.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The farewell exhortation (v5) reproduces the Shema\'s ethical content: love YHWH, walk in his ways, keep commands, hold fast (<em>dābaq</em>), serve with all heart and soul (Deut 6:5; 10:12-13; 11:22). This is not casual piety language but the formal covenant obligation — the terms of the suzerainty treaty that defines Israel\'s relationship to YHWH. Joshua is commissioning the eastern tribes for civilian life with the same content Moses used to commission Israel at the Jordan.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The blessing and dismissal are formal covenant acts. Joshua blesses them — the same verb used for priestly blessings (Num 6:23-26) — and sends them home. The departure from Shiloh (the covenant assembly site) back to their Transjordanian territory marks the transition from the corporate conquest phase to the tribal settlement phase.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The parenthetical clarification about the two half-tribes of Manasseh explains a possible confusion: one half received Bashan (east Jordan) from Moses, the other received western territory from Joshua. The distribution of the Manassite tribe across the Jordan reflects the complexity of tribal identity when a single clan had interests on both sides of the boundary.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Return to your homes with great wealth" — the material dimension of the conquest\'s success. The plunder list (large herds, silver, gold, bronze, iron, clothing) echoes the Deuteronomic promise that covenant faithfulness would result in material blessing (Deut 28:11-12). Joshua instructs them to share the plunder with the "fellow Israelites" who did not cross — a principle of solidarity: the eastern tribes had kept their covenant obligations to the western tribes; the western tribes now fulfill their obligation by sharing the material fruit.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The return to Gilead — "their own, which they had acquired according to the LORD\'s command through Moses" — grounds the eastern territory in the same Mosaic authority as the western allotments. The eastern tribes\' land is not a concession or a second-class inheritance; it was divinely authorized through Moses just as the western land was. The narrative insists on the equal covenant standing of both groups.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The altar "by the Jordan — a very large altar (<em>mizbēaḥ-gādôl lemarʾeh</em>, great to the sight)" triggers the crisis. Deut 12:5-14 had explicitly prohibited sacrificing at any location other than the place YHWH would choose — the centralization of worship was the core of Deuteronomy\'s cultic reform program. A new altar near the Jordan would violate this principle and raise the specter of unauthorized sacrifice and eventually syncretism with Canaanite altars.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The report reaches the Israelites in Canaan — phrased as news that spread through the community. "At the entrance to the land of Canaan, in the region of the Jordan, on the Israelite side" — the location is ambiguous. Is this on the Canaanite (west) side or the Transjordanian side? The ambiguity matters: if it is on the Canaanite side, it is within the territory where Deut 12 centralization law would apply; if on the Transjordanian side, its legal status might differ.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"The entire Israelite community assembled at Shiloh and prepared to go to war" — the assembly at the covenant center (Shiloh, where the tabernacle stood) to deliberate on a potential covenant violation is the proper institutional response. The threat of civil war reflects the seriousness of cultic apostasy in the Deuteronomistic framework: the Baal-Peor incident (Num 25) and Achan\'s sin (Josh 7) had both demonstrated that one community member\'s unfaithfulness could bring YHWH\'s judgment on all Israel. The community\'s readiness for war is not overreaction but covenant self-defense.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Sending a delegation before military action — Phinehas and ten tribal leaders — reflects the procedural requirement to exhaust diplomatic remedies before war (cf. Deut 20:10-12, the requirement to offer peace terms before besieging). The delegation is constituted with authority: Phinehas as priest represents the cultic concern, ten tribal heads represent the political community.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Ten leaders — one per tribe — mirrors the structure of legal proceedings requiring witnesses and judges from the whole community. The "head of his tribal clan" status of each delegate establishes their authority to represent Israel\'s covenant interest. This is not an informal embassy but a formal judicial-diplomatic mission.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The formal speech begins in v16 — the delegates arrive and present the whole community\'s charge. The journey to Gilead itself represents the community\'s willingness to pursue resolution before violence, in contrast to the immediate military mobilization of v12.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"This is what the whole community of the LORD says" — the speech is presented as a community indictment, not a personal complaint. "Treachery against the God of Israel" (<em>maʿal bēʾlōhê yiśrāʾēl</em>) — the term <em>maʿal</em> is the technical covenant term for unfaithful breach of trust, used in the Achan story (Josh 7:1, 22:20) and in the Baal-Peor narrative (Num 31:16). The charge is maximally serious: covenant treason.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Was the sin of Peor not enough?" — Baal-Peor (Num 25) was the Israelite apostasy with Moabite women and the Baal cult, which resulted in a plague killing 24,000 (Num 25:9). The wound is still fresh: "we have still not fully cleansed ourselves of it." This reference to ongoing cultic uncleanness from a historical event is significant — covenant unfaithfulness was not merely a legal category but a spiritual contamination with ongoing effects.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Tomorrow he will be angry with the entire community of Israel" — the Deuteronomistic principle of corporate solidarity: Israel is covenant community, not a collection of individuals. YHWH\'s anger at part of Israel falls on the whole. This was demonstrated at Ai (7:1-5) where Israel as a whole failed because of one man\'s sin. The western tribes\' fear is not irrational; it reflects a sophisticated understanding of how covenant worked.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"If the land you possess is somehow unclean" — the west offers a remarkable concession: come and take land on our side rather than set up a separate altar. The willingness to share land west of Jordan in order to maintain cultic unity is a remarkable expression of the priority of covenant community over territorial interest. The offer reveals that the concern is not territorial protection but religious solidarity.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The Achan precedent (<em>Achan son of Zerah</em>, cf. Josh 7) is invoked explicitly: "the LORD\'s anger fell on all Israel. He was not the only one who died for that sin." This is the clearest statement of the principle of corporate responsibility. Achan\'s sin brought military defeat and death to others; the eastern tribes\' potential apostasy could similarly bring judgment on the whole nation.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The eastern tribes\' response begins with an oath formula and moves to a denial and explanation. The formal "then answered" (<em>wayyaʿanû</em>) signals a judicial proceeding — the accused responding to a formal charge. The Reubenites, Gadites, and Manassites present themselves not as suspects but as wrongly accused parties with a legitimate defense.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"The Mighty One, God, the LORD!" — El, Elohim, YHWH — the threefold divine name is a solemn oath formula (cf. Ps 50:1). Invoking all three names simultaneously calls on the full range of divine authority as witness. "He knows, and let Israel know" — they appeal first to YHWH\'s omniscience before Israel\'s judgment. This is the structure of an oath of innocence: what is hidden from human judges is known to YHWH.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"If we built it to offer burnt offerings, grain offerings, or fellowship offerings on it — may the LORD himself call us to account." This is a conditional self-curse: the most powerful form of oath in the ANE. The speaker invites divine judgment if the accusation is true. It is impossible to use this oath form and not mean it — the invocation of divine punishment on oneself if lying was the ultimate guarantee of truthfulness.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"We were afraid that in the future your children might say to our children, \'What do you have to do with the LORD, the God of Israel?\'" — the anxiety is transgenerational. The Jordan as a geographical boundary could become a theological boundary: future generations might deny that the Transjordanian tribes had any share in YHWH\'s covenant. The altar is a preemptive response to a future exclusion they foresaw.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"The LORD has made the Jordan a boundary between us and you" — the fear that the river would function as a covenant boundary, separating the Transjordanian tribes from the covenant community. This is a sophisticated theological concern: geography could encode theological status. The Transjordanian tribes were anxious that their descendants would be treated as outsiders to the covenant community, like the nations whose lands bordered Israel.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The altar as a <em>witness</em> monument rather than a sacrificial altar: this distinction is the crux of the defense. The altar was not for use but for testimony — a stone monument declaring the Transjordanian tribes\' covenant participation. ANE treaty-witness monuments (masseboth, pillars, heaps of stones) served exactly this function: they were tangible evidence of covenant relationships for future generations. Jacob and Laban erected such a witness heap at Mizpah (Gen 31:44-52).</p>',
    "27": '<p>"A witness between us and you and the generations that come after us — that we will serve the LORD before him." The altar\'s inscription, so to speak, is that the Transjordanian tribes worship YHWH through the legitimate sacrificial system at the tabernacle. The altar is not a rival cult center but a covenant marker, like a boundary stone recording property rights. Its message is inclusion, not separation.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Look at the copy (<em>tabnît</em>) of the LORD\'s altar" — the word <em>tabnît</em> means "form, pattern, copy." The altar is explicitly patterned after the legitimate altar at the tabernacle — a reproduction for memorial purposes, not a functional alternative. This addresses the Deut 12 concern directly: they were not establishing a new worship site but erecting a permanent reminder of their connection to the central site.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"Far be it from us to rebel against the LORD or to turn away from him today by building an altar for burnt offerings, grain offerings, or sacrifices — other than the altar of the LORD our God." The explicit repudiation of any intention to use the altar for sacrifice is the final element of the defense. The Deuteronomic centralization law applied to functional altars; a memorial structure serving as a covenant witness fell outside its scope.</p>',
    "30": '<p>Phinehas and the leaders "were satisfied" (<em>wayyîṭab bəʿênêhem</em>, "it was good in their eyes") — the delegation accepts the explanation. The shift from near-war to satisfaction is complete. The Transjordanian tribes\' explanation was not merely plausible; it was theologically coherent and their oath of innocence was taken seriously.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Today we know that the LORD is among us, because you have not been unfaithful to him." Phinehas\'s conclusion inverts the covenant logic: the eastern tribes\' faithfulness is evidence of YHWH\'s presence among the whole community. "You have rescued the Israelites from the LORD\'s judgment" — had the altar been what it appeared, and had the community failed to address it, YHWH\'s judgment would have fallen on all Israel. The crisis averted was a crisis of covenant integrity for the whole community.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The report returned to Canaan closes the diplomatic loop. The formal structure — mission sent, charge delivered, response received, report returned — follows standard ANE diplomatic protocol. The speed and thoroughness of the process reflects the gravity with which covenant matters were handled.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"The report pleased the Israelites, and they praised God." The community\'s response is relief expressed as worship — the crisis was not merely resolved but resolved in a way that demonstrated covenant integrity on both sides. The addition "they spoke no more about going to war" acknowledges how close civil war had come. The narrative is honest about the danger.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"The Reubenites and Gadites named the altar Ed — \'Witness.\'" The naming of the altar formalizes its memorial function. Naming a stone monument after its function (witness, memorial, heap of testimony) was standard ANE practice (cf. Gen 31:47-49). The altar \'Ed\' would stand as permanent visible testimony that the Transjordanian tribes acknowledged YHWH as God — a counter-monument to the fear that future generations would deny their covenant inclusion.</p>'
  },
  "23": {
    "1": '<p>"After a long time" — the Hebrew <em>yāmîm rabbîm</em> (many days) is the same phrase used in 11:18 to describe the long duration of the campaigns. Joshua is now described as "old and getting on in years" (<em>zāqēn bā bayyāmîm</em>) — the same words used when the land distribution began in 13:1. This closing frame matches the opening of the distribution section, signaling the completion of Joshua\'s era.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The formal assembly — elders, leaders, judges, and officers — mirrors the administrative structure of the Mosaic governance system (Deut 1:15; 16:18). This is not a casual gathering but a formal covenant assembly. Joshua is exercising his final act of authority: a farewell address in the pattern of Moses\'s Deuteronomic speeches. The parallels to Moses are deliberate and theologically freighted.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"It was the LORD your God who fought for you" — the divine warrior motif that has run through the conquest narrative is the foundation of the entire address. Joshua does not say "we fought and won" but "you saw what YHWH did." The military record is reframed as a theological testimony: Israel\'s experience is primary evidence for YHWH\'s character and power, not Israel\'s military capability.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"The remaining nations — along with all the nations I have already wiped out" — acknowledges the incompleteness of the conquest frankly. Joshua has allotted territories that include nations not yet driven out. The program is normative (all the land from the Jordan to the Mediterranean is yours) even where occupation is not yet complete. This honest acknowledgment sets up the conditional warnings of vv12-13.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"The LORD your God himself will push them back and drive them away from you" — the future tense is conditional on Israel\'s obedience. The divine initiative is promised but not automatic: YHWH will continue the conquest if Israel maintains covenant loyalty. This conditional framing is the pivot of the entire address — past faithfulness (vv3-4) grounds future promise (v5) which is conditioned on present obedience (vv6-11).</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Everything written in the Book of the Law of Moses" — the written Torah as the authoritative covenant text. This reference to a written document is significant: Deut 17:18-20 required the king to have his own copy; Josh 1:8 required Joshua to meditate on it day and night. The written text is the normative standard, not oral tradition or priestly interpretation alone. "Without turning aside to the right or to the left" is the Deuteronomic idiom for absolute covenant compliance (Deut 5:32, 17:11, 28:14).</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Do not associate with these nations" — not political isolation but cultic separation. Specifically: do not invoke their gods\' names, swear by them, serve them, or bow to them. The progression — from naming to swearing to serving to bowing — is a gradualist description of syncretism. Merely invoking the name of a Canaanite god in an oath was the first step toward formal worship; the prohibition covers the beginning of the trajectory, not just its end.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Hold fast to the LORD your God" (<em>dābaq bəYHWH ʾĕlōhêkem</em>) — the verb <em>dābaq</em> is the intimate covenant attachment term used in Gen 2:24 for the husband-wife bond ("a man shall leave his father and mother and hold fast to his wife"). The covenant relationship between Israel and YHWH is described with the language of the most intimate human relationship. Apostasy is not merely rule-breaking but marital infidelity — a metaphor the prophets will develop extensively.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"The LORD has driven out great and powerful nations before you." The conquest summary reinforces the address\'s opening: this is what YHWH has already done. The present covenant obligation is not a theoretical demand but a response to demonstrated divine action. The rhetorical structure is gift → gratitude → obligation: YHWH gave the land; Israel\'s response is covenant loyalty.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"One of you can rout a thousand, because the LORD your God fights for you." This echo of Deut 32:30 and Lev 26:8 invokes the covenant multiplication principle: divine empowerment exponentially exceeds human capacity. The promise is not military optimization but theological: the factor of a thousand represents YHWH\'s presence as the primary combatant. Conversely, the same texts warn that covenant violation will reverse this ratio — Israel will flee from their enemies rather than routing them (Deut 28:25).</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Be very careful in your hearts to love the LORD your God" — the inner disposition (<em>lēbāb</em>, heart) is the locus of covenant fidelity. Deuteronomy consistently moves from external compliance to internal orientation: the law is to be written on the heart (Deut 6:6), circumcision of the heart is the ultimate demand (Deut 10:16, 30:6). Joshua\'s final exhortation targets the same interiority — not merely correct behavior but the orientation of desire and loyalty.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"If you turn away" — the conditional reversal begins. Intermarriage (<em>bənetatem... ûlqaḥtem</em>) with the remaining nations will create kinship ties that erode covenant separation. Deut 7:3-4 prohibited intermarriage specifically because foreign wives would "turn your sons away from following me." The concern is not ethnic but cultic: family bonds create the most powerful social pressure toward adopting the religious practices of one\'s spouse and in-laws.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Snares and traps... whips on your backs and thorns in your eyes" — Exod 23:33 ("they will be a snare to you") and Num 33:55 ("thorns in your eyes") are the background texts. The metaphors describe invisible entrapments (snare), painful constraint (whip), and constant irritation (thorn) — three different aspects of the ongoing cost of incomplete covenant obedience. The concluding threat — "until you perish from this good land" — points forward to the Babylonian exile that the Deuteronomistic History is moving toward.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Now I am about to go the way of all the earth" — the euphemism for death uses the universal human experience. Joshua identifies with the common human condition rather than claiming special exemption. "You know with all your heart and soul that not one of all the good promises the LORD has made to you has failed" — the covenant record is complete and verifiable. The claim is not theoretical but based on Israel\'s lived experience of YHWH\'s faithfulness.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The symmetry of divine word-keeping: "just as every good thing the LORD your God promised you has come upon you, so he will also bring upon you every evil he has threatened." This is the logical structure of covenant theology — the same faithfulness that brought blessing will bring curse if the conditions are violated. YHWH\'s trustworthiness is not selective: the threatened punishments of Deut 28:15-68 are as certain as the realized blessings of Deut 28:1-14.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"If you violate the covenant of the LORD your God... the LORD\'s anger will burn against you, and you will quickly perish from this good land he has given you." The phrase "good land" appears three times in vv13-16, bracketing the warning with the reminder of what is at stake. The land is gift, not possession by right; it is held conditionally on covenant faithfulness. Joshua\'s last words set up the entire historical trajectory of Judges through Kings: Israel will violate the covenant, the good land will be lost, and the Deuteronomistic History will interpret every disaster through this framework.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua')
    merge_comm(existing, JOSHUA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'joshua', existing)
    print('Joshua 21-23 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
